Traffic Impact Study, Centennial Park Pool Renovation, Park Ridge, Illinois
This report presents the results of a traffic impact analysis undertaken for the proposed renovation of an outdoor
swimming pool facility located at 100 South Western Avenue, Park Ridge, IL 60068. The outdoor swimming pool
facility is part of existing Centennial Park which also includes a community center, senior center, sledding hill,
baseball fields, soccer fields, playground, and picnic area. Centennial Park is located on the southwest corner of the
intersection of Western Avenue and Touhy Avenue as shown in the Site Location Map (Exhibit 1).
The proposed renovation of the existing swimming pool facility will increase the pool capacity from 917 to 1000
persons. The parking capacity of Centennial Park will be increased to 330 stalls by adding 82 new parking stalls as
part of the proposed renovation. No changes are proposed to the Community Center, Senior Center, sledding hill and
baseball fields. The new pool will require the relocation of the playground area, two bocce courts and picnic area and
elimination of two youth soccer fields, all which are currently located on the site.
Access to Centennial Park is provided via two 2-way existing driveways and one exit-only driveway on Western
Avenue. Exhibit 2 presents the site plan of Centennial Park showing the proposed swimming facility location and the
The renovation is scheduled to take place in a single construction phase and the new pool facility anticipated to be
operational by July 2014. This report evaluates the following traffic conditions:

 Projected Year (2018) without the proposed development

City of Park Ridge is a Chicago suburb with a population of 37,480 (2010 census) located at about 14 miles
from downtown Chicago and two miles east of O’Hare International Airport. Centennial Park is located at
the southwest corner of the intersection of Touhy Avenue and Western Avenue.
Touhy Avenue: Touhy Avenue is an undivided four lane road in the east-west direction with a posted speed limit of
35 mph, west of Western Avenue and 30 mph, east of Western Avenue. The Annual Average Daily Traffic (AADT) on
this road, obtained from IDOT’s GIS Traffic Maps is 30,600 vehicles.
Western Avenue: Western Avenue is an undivided two lane road in the north-south direction with a posted speed
limit 25 mph north of Touhy Avenue. The post speed limit south of Touhy Avenue is 20 mph when children are
present. Western Avenue is a designated bike route and truck traffic is not permitted on this roadway.
Garden Street: Garden Street is a two lane residential roadway, primarily providing access to about 10-15 houses on
the street. The traffic on Garden Street is assumed to be very low and local in nature.
Western Avenue/Touhy Avenue Intersection: The project site is located on the southwest corner of the intersection of
Western Avenue and Touhy Avenue. This is a signalized intersection. The east and west approaches have one
shared thru/left turn lane and one shared thru/right turn lane. The north and south approaches have one lane in each
direction. High visibility crosswalks exist on all four legs of the intersection.
Western Avenue/Driveway 1/Garden Street Intersection: This is a 2-way stop controlled intersection. The low traffic
on Garden Street is assumed to have minimal effect on the operations at this intersection. With low traffic volumes,
this intersection is assumed to operate at acceptable levels of service during all analyses traffic conditions.
Adjacent properties to Centennial Park are primarily residential. There are two schools in the vicinity of the
project site. Lincoln Middle School is located in the northwestern quadrant of the intersection of Western

To observe the traffic pattern on Western Avenue, 24-hour machine counts were obtained at the locations just north

Touhy Avenue on Western Avenue, in a 24-hour period was observed to be 3445. The traffic volume drops down to

The swimming pool usage season is typically from Memorial Day to Labor Day. Peak usage data for various facilities
in the Park has been obtained from the park district staff. In order to provide a conservative approach the peak
existing “worst case scenario” site traffic was estimated and added to the existing turning movement counts at the
intersection of Touhy Ave and Western Avenue. It is also to be noted that the peak of Centennial Park traffic does not
coincide with the peak of the adjacent street traffic. Again for a conservative approach it is assumed that these peaks
coincide. Table 1 and 2 are presented with the summer AM and PM peak traffic generated by Centennial Park.

The proposed swimming pool facility renovation will have an increase of 83 persons for a capacity of 1,000 persons.
Proposed swimming pool facility will consist of existing wading pool; new 8-lane 25 yard combination lap and diving
pool with 1 meter diving board; and new leisure pool with zero depth entry play, play features, body flume slides,
water walk, 3-lane lap swimming, water volleyball, and water basketball.
No changes are proposed to the Community Center, Senior Center, sledding hill and baseball fields. The new pool
will require the relocation of the playground area, two bocce courts and picnic area and elimination of the two existing
youth soccer fields, all which are currently located on the site. No new trips are generated due to this relocation as
there is no change in the size of these facilities.
Site access will remain at the two existing access points Driveway 1 and Driveway 2. The third driveway on the
south, Driveway 3, will remain to be used as an exit-only driveway.
The parking is proposed to be increased by 82 stalls making the overall site parking total of 330 stalls. The central
parking lot will have 9 stalls for handicap parking. During peak summer usage the parking facilities include the
parking lot on the Centennial Park site and also adjacent overflow parking at the Lincoln Middle School and the
Washington Elementary School through a joint use agreement between Park Ridge Park District and School District

Site ingress/egress traffic at the site driveways and at the study area intersection was distributed based on
the current travel patterns observed via traffic counts for the study area. It is assumed that 90% of the site
traffic is from/to north as Touhy Avenue is an important roadway, providing access to the nearest freeway,
I-294 on the west. Exhibit 4.0 shows the site traffic distribution.

As the surrounding area of the project site is totally built-up it is assumed that the traffic in this area will
grow at a minimal rate. A nominal growth rate of 0.5 percent per year was used to estimate the future traffic
volumes. This growth rate was also used in a recent traffic impact study in the City of Park Ridge, titled “
Traffic Impact Study, Proposed Whole Foods Market, Park Ridge, Illinois” completed in March 2012. This
growth rate was used to project existing traffic volumes to the 2018 No-build condition.
The new trips expected to be generated due to the renovation of the swimming pool is added to the future
year No-build condition traffic volume to obtain future (build) year traffic volumes. Exhibit 5 and 6 show the
2018 No-build and 2018 build traffic volumes at the intersection of Touhy Avenue and Western Avenue.

Intersection capacity analysis was performed for the study area intersection. Synchro
analyze the study intersection for the current and future conditions according to methods presented in the
Transportation Research Board’s Highway Capacity Manual (HCM 2010).
The Level of Service (LOS) of an intersection ranges from A to F where LOS A has a low vehicular delay indicating
smooth free-flowing traffic. LOS F has a high vehicular delay and indicates the worst-case scenario with high
congestion and a complete breakdown of traffic flow. LOS A through C are the desired levels for rural areas. LOS D
is considered acceptable only in urban conditions. Traffic conditions with LOS of E or F are generally deemed
unacceptable and represent significant travel delay, increased accident potential, and inefficient motor vehicle
operation. Table 4 shows the relation between LOS and vehicular delay for signalized and un-signalized

In the 2018 future No-build conditions the intersection is anticipated to continue operating at an acceptable level of

In the 2018 future No-build conditions the intersection is anticipated to operate at an acceptable level of service C or
